sthityutpattisaṃdarśanārthamityapare /	According to another opinion, the first formula indicates duration, and the second indicates arising;
yāvat kāraṇasrotastāvat kāryasroto bhavati /	As long as the flux of causes asts, the fiix of results exists;

 for the destruction of conditioned things is spontaneous; it does not come from anything;
kiṃ kāraṇam /	it does not depend on a cause.
kāryasya hi kāraṇaṃ bhavati / vanāśaścābhāvaḥ /	That which depends on a cause is an effect, something done," "created.

 There are four types of questions: 1.
ekāṃśavyākaraṇīyo vibhajyavyākaraṇīyaḥ paripṛcchayya vyākaraṇīyaḥ sthāpanīyaśca /	a question to which one responds in a categorical manner; a question to which one responds by distinguishing; a question to which one responds by another question;
tatra yathākramaṃ veditavyam /	and 4.
ekāṃśato vyākaraṇaṃ vibhajya paripṛcchaya ca /	a question which one should not answer.
sthāpyaṃ ca maraṇotpatti viśiṣṭātmā 'nyatādivat //	Categorical response, as for death; a distinguishing response, as for rebirth; a response by a question, as for superiority;
kiṃ sarvasattvā mariṣyantītyekāṃśena vyākarttavyaṃ mariṣyantīti /	and a response by rejecting the question, as for non-identity. If one asks, Do all beings die," one should answer in a.

 Furthermore, the abandoning which results from the worldly path is supported, confirmed by the pure possession of disconnection, as it results from the fact that, by virtue of this pure possession, the Sakṛ̥dāgāmin and the Anāgāmin cannot die in a state of falling away: they can lose their qualities, but they take them up again before dying.
yadeva caitacchrāmaṇyayuktaṃ /	Śrāmaṇya or the religious life is brāhmaṇya;
brāhmaṇyaṃ brahmacakraṃ ca tadeva	it is brahmacakra.
kleśānāṃ vāhanādvāhmaṇyaṃ brahmacakraṃ tu	It is brahmacakra because it expels the defilements;
brahmāvartanāt /	it is brahmacakra, the Wheel of Brahmā, because it is set into motion by Brahmā.
anuttarabrahmaṇyayogāt bhagavānbrahmā /	The Blessed One, possessing supreme ōrāhḥmaṇya, is Brahmā.
“eṣa hi bhagavān brahmā ityapi śāntaḥ śītībhūta ityapī“ti sūtrāt /	It says that the Blessed One is calm and pacified. This caéra belongs to him;
tasyedaṃ cakramiti brāhmaṃ tena prartitatvāt /	this caekra is therefore of Brahmā, because he sets it into motion.
dharmacakraṃ tu dṛṅmārgaḥ	The Wheel of the Dharma is the Path of Seeing.
caṅkramaṇāccakraṃ tatsādharmyāddarśanamārgo dharmacakram /	It is termed wheel, cakra, because it moves. The Path of Seeing, being of the nature of a wheel (a Jewel of a Wheel, cakraratna), is called the Wheel of the Dharma.
kathamasya sādharmyam /	How is the Path of Seeing of the nature of a wheel?
āśugatvādyarādibhiḥ //	Because it goes quickly, etc. ; because it has spokes, etc. Because it goes quickly, for it comprehends the Truths in fifteen moments of thought; because it leaves one spot and occupies another, leaving the Irresistible Path and occupying the Path of Deliverance;
āśugatvāttyajanakramaṇāt ajitajayajitādhyavasanādutpatananipattanācca /	because it subdues the unsubdued and rules over those subdued, triumphing over the defilements through the Irresistible Path by cutting off the possession of these defilements; ruḻing over the vanquished defilements by the Path of Deliverance. By obtaining possession of disconnection from these defilements; because it rises and descends, either because it is alternatively the Irresistible Path and the Path of Deliverance, or because it successively takes as its object Kāmadhātu and the higher spheres.
evamāśugatvādibhiḥ arādibhiḥ sādharmyādāryāṣṭāṅṅgo mārgaścakramiti bhadantaghoṣakaḥ /	The Bhadanta Ghoṣaka says: The Noble Eightfold Path is a wheel, because its parts are in the nature of spokes, etc. Right Views, Right Thought, Right Effort, and Right Mindfulness are similar to spokes;
samyagdṛṣṭisaṃkalpavyāyāmasmṛtayo hyarasthānīyāḥ /	Right Speech, Right Actions, and Right Livelihood are similar to the axle;
samyagvākkarmāntājīvā nābhisthānīyāḥ samādhirnemisthānīya iti darśanamārgo dharmacakramiti /	and Right Concentration is similar to the rim. On what rests the doctrine that the Wheel of the Dharma is the Path of Seeing the Truths?
kuta etat āryakauṇḍinyasya tadutpattau “pravarttitaṃ dharmacakrami“ti vacanāt /	On the Āgama which says that, at the moment when this Path arose within the Āryan Kauṇḍinya, declared that the Wheel of the Dharma had been set into motion.
kathaṃ tattriparivartaṃ dvādaśākāraṃ ca /	How is this Path of threefold revolution and of twelve aspects?
idaṃ duḥkhamāryasatyam /	The Vaibhāṣikas say: The three revolutions are “this is the Noble Truth of Suffering”;
tat khalu parijñeyaṃ tat khalu parijñātamityete trayaḥ parivartāḥ /	“It should be perfectly known”.
ekaikasmiṃśca parivarte cakṣurudapādi jñānaṃ vidyā buddhirudapādi ityete dvādaśākārāḥ /	At each revolution there arises sight, knowledge, knowing, and intelligence. Thus we have twelve aspects.
pratisatyemevaṃ bhavanti / trikadvādaśakasādharmyāttu triparivartaṃ dvādaśākāramuktam /	The same holds true for the other Truths: This is the Origin of Suffering," etc. Since the revolutions and the aspects are the same for each Truth, the Wheel of the Dharma is of three revolutions and twelve aspects; not of twelve revolutions and forty-eight aspects.
